The Akwa Ibom State government has prohibited all public burials, weddings and other forms of gatherings till further notice. It came into effect following the signing into law the quarantine and restriction of movement regulations 2020 by Governor Udom Emmanuel. The government also set up a task force to enforce the new law that will be in place till the COVID-19 pandemic is over. In a statement signed by Sir Charles Udoh, the commissioner for Information, the government vowed to prosecute defaulters under the new law. The law directed that all places of religious worship, churches, and mosques shall strictly observe the social distancing prescription of a minimum of one metre and not more than 20 persons per gathering. In addition to hand washing facility with running water, soap and sanitisers shall be made available. Also, all public parks, shops, eateries, clubs, restaurants, markets and offices within the state shall remain closed except for the sale of foodstuffs, drugs and other essential commodities.